NAAM_LANG: Master's Aquaculture and Marine Resource Management
INTERNATIONALE_NAAM: Master's Aquaculture and Marine Resource Management
EIGENNAAM: Master's Aquaculture and Marine Resource Management
EIGENNAAM_ENGELS: Master's Aquaculture and Marine Resource Management
OMSCHRIJVING:
The MSc programme Aquaculture and Marine Resource Management trains academic professionals in the field of the sustainable use, conservation and restauration of marine and aquatic ecosystems and resources, by combining ecological, technological, and socio-economic approaches. Oceans, seas, estuaries, rivers and lakes play a major role in feeding the world, but also provide numerous other goods and services. To ensure continued use of the world's marine regions and aquatic ecosystems and resources, integrated and interdisciplinary strategies towards sustainability are needed. After an interdisciplinary common part, students specialize in one of three following fields:  
a) Aquaculture  
This specialisation deals with the culture of all types of aquatic organisms (such as finfish, shrimp, shellfish, corals, sponges and algae) in a wide range of culture conditions (from sea enclosures to semi-extensive ponds, high-tech on-land recirculation systems, and integrated multi-trophic aquaculture). The technical skills required for maintaining a healthy production environment are combined with the socio-economic aspects relevant for aquaculture activities. Students gain in-depth knowledge and skills on biology and physiology of aquatic organisms and develop skills in aquaculture system management.  
b) Marine Resources and Ecology  
This specialization focuses on the functioning of marine and aquatic communities in relation to human interventions, including fisheries, habitat destruction and climate change. Sustainable management of marine living resources includes the development of models of ecological interactions, population dynamics and fishery yield, international regulations, management tools, and the economics of resource use. Students study how these models are used and learn to apply them, developing insight in ecosystem engineering for coastal protection and the ecological processes that form the basis for marine food webs and their use.  
c) Marine Governance  
This specialization provides students the analytical skills and tools they need to understand marine governance and to propose innovative solutions for an effective and legitimate decision making process. This specialization focuses on social, economic and political processes of the use and management of marine resources. Students become proficient in the functioning of national and international public institutions, including the European Union and United Nations, and a range of new private governance instruments, such as Eco-certification and environmental credits.

NAAM_LANG: Master's Health Management in Aquaculture (double degree)
INTERNATIONALE_NAAM: Master's Health Management in Aquaculture (double degree)
EIGENNAAM: Master's Health Management in Aquaculture (double degree)
EIGENNAAM_ENGELS: Master's Health Management in Aquaculture (double degree)
OMSCHRIJVING: The International Master of Science in Health Management in Aquaculture (AquaH) is an Erasmus Mundus programme and a cooperation between four universities in different European countries. One of the learning lines of AquaH is an integral part of the MSc Aquaculture and Marine Resource Management (MAM) of Wageningen University, specialisation A: Aquaculture and includes the course 'Frontiers in animal health' . This particular learning line focuses on preventing diseases and maintaining adequate health, whilst minimising the impact on the environment. Admission to the MAM programme does not equal admission to AquaH because this programme has a separate admission and application procedure. After finishing the AquaH MSc programme, students will receive a double degree in both AquaH and MAM.   \n\nParticipants that successfully complete the programme, will understand the interaction between aquaculture species and their environment, and be able to help produce in a controlled way robust and healthy animals with attention for epidemiological, environmental and welfare regulations. Following a common start-up module at the University of Ghent in Belgium where fundamental issues in aquaculture health are addressed, AquaH students can continue a specific learning line at WU to focus on recent developments in fish and shellfish nutrition and health in circular aquaculture systems (recirculating aquaculture systems or ponds). Here, they will perform research into how nutrition influences and interacts with health, how novel feed ingredients can help improve disease resistance, and how to apply the latest strategies for disease prevention based on activation of the immune system, including important tools such as new generation vaccines.

Global challenges such as climate change, biodiversity conservation and the protein transition from animal-based to plant-based diets require plant-based solutions. Therefore, plant scientists require an ability to deal with the dynamics and complexity of plant production at the different organisation levels, from molecules, cells, organisms, populations and communities up to ecosystems. Therefore, the MPS programme is based on a multidisciplinary approach that combines plant biology, plant physiology, (population) genetics, ecology, epidemiology, animal biology, microbiology and soil biology. These combined disciplines are based on supporting disciplines such as statistics and mathematics, data science, biochemistry, molecular and cell biology and environmental physics.   
The Plant Sciences programme combines impact based on research, with a keen eye for developments in the global academic and professional field in a societal context. During their MSc thesis, students are trained for a career in academic research. In combination with the MSc internship and Academic Consultancy Training or Research Master Cluster, they receive real-life education based on concrete cases to grow as a researcher, technological expert, consultant, business-related R&D professional, policy maker or entrepreneur in the global agricultural sector.   
MPS-A: Specialisation Crop Science   
The protein transition from animal-based to plant-based diets and the need for biobased products imply that we must produce crops sustainably, not at the expense of biodiversity or global warming, and within planetary boundaries. Simultaneously, the climate and environmental impacts of crop production should be minimised to stabilize yield. This calls for ecophysiological understanding of how plants respond to multiple, fluctuating production and stress conditions as well as the ecological consequences in terms of interactions with the biotic environment. This understanding will lead to insights into how novel sustainable crop production affects yield variability and resource use across agro-ecosystems. Such insights can be used to develop sustainable and resilient production systems under changing agronomic, environmental and ecological conditions.  
The specialisation Crop Science takes organismal plant physiology as a starting point and focuses on the regulation of key processes such as photosynthesis, phenotypic plasticity, intra- and interspecific plant interactions, and agronomy. Quantitative modelling, simulation and data science methods are used to analyse and understand yield constraints in the development of productive resilient cropping systems.   
MPS-B: Specialisation Greenhouse Horticulture   
Protected horticulture is essential in diverse climate zones to optimize crop grow

Plant Breeding plays an important role in the development of plant varieties for healthy food, feed and sustainable bioresources. New varieties have to meet current demands regarding yield, disease resistance, quality characteristics, salt or drought tolerance and suitability for sustainable plant production systems. Plant Breeding involves a variety of aspects, ranging from the molecular level to the population level and requires knowledge on the physiology, ecology and genetics of cultivated plants. The use of various genomics related techniques as well as bioinformatics and data science contributes enormously to the rapid identification of genes for natural resistance and is essential for accelerating the selection process by marker-assisted breeding.

This MSc programme offers forefront insights from business sciences, providing a multi-disciplinary perspective on how firms, farms, markets and sectors transform to be part of sustainable solutions. It offers and develops knowledge, skills and competencies to become a manager, marketeer, or entrepreneur that can run a business beyond the usual, making it suited for a more sustainable future. In the first year students build up a knowledge base, first taking stock of existing business theories and the consequences of taking sustainability serious, followed by exploring solutions in the domains of strategic marketing, leadership and organizing for sustainability transitions in business. Later, students learn to creatively develop theories to enhance sustainability and innovation in business, learn advanced qualitative and quantitative methods for testing and advancing such theories, to close year one with reflections on the learnings (including ethics). Along year one, a so-called ribbon course aims at cohort building. To deepen personal skills and interests, year one includes skills modules, an academic consultancy training using a real assignment, and two elective courses. The second year is filled with the master thesis project and an internship with an external company or organization to prepare for a future job at academic level (either in the Netherlands or abroad).

This programme provides theory, tools, and techniques for generically applicable analytical methods to analyse sustainable supply chains in life sciences. The core of the programme consists of an integrated approach to the three dominant perspectives in supply chains, i.e., the material flows, the finance flows, and the information or data flows. Students foremost deepen, integrate, and apply their knowledge in:   
- management of operations and products flow control  
- economic performance, risks, and supply chain resilience  
- information technology and data science  
Moreover, students are trained to become valuable, academically skilled generalists who understand supply chain processes, envision how new developments can be applied to make a sustainable impact, and have learned how complex decision problems in supply chains should and can be solved in practice.

This MSc programme provides the knowledge and skills to analyse consumers making choices, acquiring products and services, using these products and services and disposing of them. To understand consumers in all their complexity, this program combines insights from psychology, economics, design, and sociology, in an interdisciplinary approach. In-depth academic insights are provided with views of the consumer as an individual, part of a household, and member of society. In addition, the Wageningen collaborations across the agriculture, environment and food domains allows students to learn the skills needed to effectively collaborate in teams with people from diverse backgrounds.  \n\nThe first year starts with the course Consumer studies for sustainability: Perspectives and ethics, combining the different social scientific insights and providing the basis for the program. The first year also contains two courses that show the integration of consumer and natural sciences Sensory perception and consumer preferences and Consumer, technology and innovation. Included in the first year is also the Academic Master Cluster, in which teams of 5 to 7 students from different disciplines realize a transdisciplinary academic consulting project for a real company or other stakeholder. Nearing the end of the first year and to preaper for the thesis in the second year, students learn to integrate theoretical insights and to build a conceptual model in the course Advanced consumer studies. Finally there are courses to fill the methodological toolbox with advanced quantitative and/or advanced qualitative methods. By choosing your own electives (18 ECTS), students can deepen and broaden their knowledge in specific topics or areas of interest, for example to prepare for a desired labour market profile. The second year is filled with the master thesis project and an internship with an external company or organisation to prepare for a future job at academic level (either in the Netherlands or abroad).

This MSc program focuses on the interactions between economic actors and the natural environment. Students are trained as quantitative economists, able to analyze real-world problems in food systems, natural resources and the living environment, and to provide economic solutions that promote transitions to a sustainable future. Besides a strong training in quantitative economic techniques, students are confronted with a wide variety of relevant economic theories at micro, behavioral, and institutional level to help understand the nature of sustainability problems and to propose solutions.  

The first year of the program starts with an overview of traditional neoclassical economic theories and alternative heterodox theories in order to broaden the theoretical window on real world sustainability issues. Theoretical knowledge can be deepened by choosing either a short course on Behavioral Economics or Political Economy. In the courses Advanced Econometrics and Modeling Sustainability Challenges students develop the necessary methodological expertise for quantitative economic analysis of sustainability issues. Then, a specific thesis trajectory is chosen via one of the three available thesis preparing courses. In the first year students also work on an interdisciplinary project in the Academic Master Cluster and engage with philosophy of science and ethics. Finally, there is space for 18 elective credits in the first year to deepen and broaden the knowledge in specific topics or areas, to prepare for a desired labour market and academic profile.  

The second year is filled with the master thesis project and an internship with an external company or organization to prepare for a future job at an academic level (either in the Netherlands or abroad).

This MSc programme aims to educate future leaders in governments, NGOs and academia involved in governing sustainability challenges. It provides in-depth understanding on the social, political and legal dimensions of transformative governance and on the ways to put this to work in designs of and negotiations over novel governance arrangements. The programme' s embeddedness in Wageningen University of Life Sciences creates opportunities for the development of true interdisciplinary skills and science for impact, which are needed to address today's and future grand sustainability challenges.  \n\nThe first year of the programme starts with an overview of these grand challenges for the governance of sustainability transformations. In subsequent courses of the first year, sustainability transformations will be dealt with from different angles, including legal, social and policy perspectives. Towards the end of the first year a research design course will prepare for doing the thesis in the second year, and do so in an ethical and inclusive way. The first year ends with a choice option between the Academic Master Cluster and the European Workshop Environmental Sciences and Management. Both these courses aim at doing interdisciplinary consultancy research in a team of students from different disciplines. Finally, there is an elective space of 18 credits in the first year to deepen and broaden the knowledge in specific topics or areas of one's own interest, to prepare for a desired labour market and academic profile. The second year is filled with the master thesis project and an internship with an external company or organization to prepare for a future job at academic level (either in the Netherlands or abroad).

NAAM_LANG: Master Management, Economics and Consumer Studies (DD)
INTERNATIONALE_NAAM: Master Management, Economics and Consumer Studies (DD)
EIGENNAAM: Master Management, Economics and Consumer Studies (DD)
EIGENNAAM_ENGELS: Master Management, Economics and Consumer Studies (DD)
OMSCHRIJVING: This is the DD MME programme for incoming students from Bonn and Cremona. The focus of the DD MSc programme Management, Economics and Consumer Studies is on the managerial, economic, environmental and social aspects of the production and consumption of food and other agricultural products within households and businesses in a sustainable and dynamic environment. This complex system asks for an integration of social sciences and natural sciences, which is an important aspects of the programme.

The MSc programme International Development Studies addresses worldwide social transformation processes related to livelihoods, agro-food networks and the environment within a dynamic international context. The programme delivers graduates who are able to study these transformation processes independently in an integrated way, in a comparative perspective and at different levels (local, regional, national and international). Special attention is given to inclusion and exclusion processes, equity and unequal access to resources. The programme not only gives students a critical understanding of social transformation processes, but also teaches students to integrate and share their knowledge, include the diverging views of different stakeholders, and work in multidisciplinary teams.   \nStudents can choose one of four specializations: Sociology of Development; Economics of Development; Inclusive Innovation, Communication and Development; Politics and Governance of Development. In the specialization part students study the domain from corresponding disciplinary-based perspectives. The programme is thesis-oriented with an individual research project.   \nGraduates of the programme are well prepared to continue academic training (PhD) or for a professional role in research, education/training, advice, consultancy and policy making.

The MSc programme Animal Sciences is a logical continuation of a BSc in Animal Sciences or an equivalent BSc programme such as Veterinary Sciences or Animal Biology. The focus of this MSc programme is to deliver skilled professional animal scientists, well equipped to tackle problems related to sustainable management of animals that are an integral part of our society, economy and culture. Animal systems and their development are very diverse, and constrained by technical factors (e.g. food supply, animal health, level of management and genetic diversity) and infrastructural, ecological and socio-economic factors. Upon graduation, the animal sciences specialists have received a fundamental scientific training combined with a critical attitude towards all aspects determining sustainable development of animal systems.  

The study programme is an individual tailor-made thesis-oriented programme. Students follow advanced courses in their first year to prepare for the thesis in the second year. The thesis can be chosen from different disciplines, distinguished in specializations. Within specializations students can choose a thesis track at a specific chair group, that matches their interest in terms of level of study, animal species or topic.  
- Genetics and Biodiversity focuses on the genetic improvement of animals in relation to their environment, by integrating quantitative, biological and molecular approaches. Focus can be on genetic management of domestic or wildlife populations to ensure optimal health and performance, or on the genetic basis of specific behaviours or characteristics in various animal species.  
- Nutrition and Metabolism aims to understand the relation between nutritional demands, diet formulation, digestion and metabolism in animals, and their responses in terms of growth, production, well-being and waste. The aim is to optimize nutrition for the production of safe and healthy foods for human consumption, to safeguard the animal's own health and welfare and to prevent negative effects of nutrition on the emission of waste to the environment.  
- Global and Sustainable Production combines knowledge from different disciplines (such as animal sciences, economics and social sciences) to study the development of sustainable animal systems across the world. The aim is to guarantee sufficient food supply for mankind in a responsible way, without compromising culture and the environment.  
- Adaptation, Health and Behaviour studies the effects of the immediate environment on physiological responses of individual or groups of animals, and what these responses mean for animal health and welfare. Immunological status, energy metabolism, thermoregulation, reproduction and behaviour are major responses of animals being studied in this specia

NAAM_LANG: European master's Animal Breeding and Genetics (double degree)
INTERNATIONALE_NAAM: European master's Animal Breeding and Genetics (double degree)
EIGENNAAM: European master's Animal Breeding and Genetics (double degree)
EIGENNAAM_ENGELS: European master's Animal Breeding and Genetics (double degree)
OMSCHRIJVING: The MSc programme Animal Sciences is a logical continuation of a BSc in Animal Sciences or an equivalent BSc programme such as Veterinary Sciences or Animal Biology. The focus of this MSc programme is to deliver skilled professional animal scientists, well equipped to tackle problems related to sustainable management of animals that are an integral part of our society, economy and culture. Animal systems and their development are very diverse, and constrained by technical factors (e.g. food supply, animal health, level of management and genetic diversity) and infrastructural, ecological and socio-economic factors. Upon graduation, the animal sciences specialists have received a fundamental scientific training combined with a critical attitude towards all aspects determining sustainable development of animal systems.  \n\nThe European Master in Animal Breeding and Genetics (EMABG) is a double degree two-year MSc programme for students that want to specialize in Animal Breeding and Genetics, developed by a consortium of six European universities. Students within this programme follow their first year at Wageningen University, and the second year at one out of three EMABG partner universities (SLU, NMBU or BOKU). They are registered to the relevant MSc programmes at both universities and receive two MSc degrees after successful completion of the EMABG programme. At Wageningen University, EMABG students are registered to the MSc Animal Sciences and they follow the current MASEM examination programme.

The MSc programme Nutrition and Health offers a theoretical background in nutrition as well as a strong methodologically oriented training.   \nThis approach enables the nutritionist to function in the area of human nutrition, but also in several related disciplines (e.g. public health, epidemiology, medical sciences, food science, etc).

NAAM_LANG: Online master's Nutritional Epidemiology and Public Health
INTERNATIONALE_NAAM: Online master's Nutritional Epidemiology and Public Health
EIGENNAAM: Online master's Nutritional Epidemiology and Public Health
EIGENNAAM_ENGELS: Online master's Nutritional Epidemiology and Public Health
OMSCHRIJVING:
The MSc programme variant Nutritional Epidemiology and Public Health offers a theoretical background in nutritional epidemiology, public health epidemiology and public health (nutrition). It includes a strong methodologically oriented training.  
This approach enables the nutritionist to function in the area of human nutrition, but also in several related disciplines (e.g. public health, epidemiology, medical sciences, food science, etc).  

This variant of the MSc Nutrition and Health is offered part-time and online. It is aimed at both students that have recently graduated from their Bachelor's programme as well as Life-Long-Learners.  
Except for a 'Wageningen Week' in the 2nd year of the programme, all course-work for the programme, including the assessment can be done online.

In the MSc programme Food Technology the student meets at a high level of abstraction advanced training in disciplines, which are related to the different courses offered in the programme. The level of this training elaborates on the background of the student in the BSc programme. Another highlight is the designing of solutions for problems in the process of producing food, which are arising in several parts of the food chain. Cognition and skills training must teach the student to communicate with colleagues from other disciplines, to analyse and comprehend a problem and to create a solution for the problem. The MSc programme is open for students that hold a BSc or equivalent in one of the following fields: Food Technology, Food Science, Chemical Engineering or related. Students with other BSc degrees will be admitted based on the actual programme in their BSc and/or relevant work experience.

The European Master in Food studies programme is a separate specialization of the MSc programme Food Technology. This specialization is open for students that hold a BSc or equivalent in Food Technology, Food Science or related, and have been admitted to the MSc Food Technology. Besides the relevant background, also the academic level, relevant work or research experience and other activities or achievements are evaluated, due to the limited placements available in this specialization (around 20 students each year).  \nThis training offers study at 4 different universities (WUR, UCC, AgroParisTech, Lund University) during the 1st year and a 9-month combined thesis project/internship in one of the 9 partner companies during the 2nd year. The level of this training elaborates on the background of the student in the BSc programme. Another highlight is the wide spectrum of knowledge offered, including food structure and behaviour, consumer studies and management, food entrepreneurship, (sustainable) food processing, food safety, product development and innovation, a 2-year team project (i.e. major product development assignment), food fermentation, food law, and soft skills training (i.e. international teamwork, leadership, negotiation, communication, networking and strategic stakeholder engagement). Cognition and skills training must teach the student to communicate with colleagues from other disciplines and major stakeholders of the programme, to analyse and comprehend a problem and to create a solution for the problem.

In the MSc programme Food Technology the student meets at a high level of abstraction advanced training in disciplines, which are related to the different specialization options of the programme. The level of this training elaborates on the background of the student in the BSc programme. Another highlight is the designing of solutions for problems in the process of producing food, which are arising in several parts of the food chain. Cognition and skills training must teach the student to communicate with colleagues from other disciplines, to analyse and comprehend a problem and to create a solution for the problem. The MSc programme is open for students that hold a BSc or equivalent in one of the following fields: Food Technology, Food Science, Chemical Engineering or related. Students with other BSc degrees will be admitted based on the actual programme in their BSc and/or relevant work experience.

NAAM_LANG: Master's Resilient Farming and Food Systems
INTERNATIONALE_NAAM: Master's Resilient Farming and Food Systems
EIGENNAAM: Master's Resilient Farming and Food Systems
EIGENNAAM_ENGELS: Master's Resilient Farming and Food Systems
OMSCHRIJVING: The Master Resilient Farming and Food Systems explores agroecosystems, sustainable food systems, and multi-functional land use from the viewpoint of various disciplines (i.e. plant, soil, animal, social and environmental sciences), multiple perspectives (i.e. sustainability, health, and ethics) and different geographical scales (local, regional, and global). A transdisciplinary systems approach characterizes both the research and education domains in the master. The programme highly values the integration of theory and practice by focusing on action learning and action research to contribute to the development of sustainable food systems. Ecological concepts are applied in various domains, including agroecology, organic agriculture, permaculture, conservation agriculture, and are connected to the economic, societal and sociological context.   \nThe master is experiential (learning by doing), authentic (departing from real-world issues and utilising real-life case studies) and interactive (involving multiple stakeholders and social learning). Courses of the compulsory core focus on an integrated approach towards exploring the future of food and farming. This provides a strong basis for the specializations Agroecology and Sustainable Food Systems. In addition, students form a community of learners where they share their academic and professional expertise in an international classroom and develop essential skills for the MSc thesis and the MSc internship. The programme prepares students for a wide range of positions in consultancy, policy, (social) entrepreneurship, or research & development that are related to multiple land use, agroecology, and sustainable food systems on a global scale.

Agroecology studies the application of ecological processes to agricultural production systems. It provides information, methods of analysis, evaluation and improvement to promote development of secure and sustainable food systems. Methods from natural and social sciences are integrated to deal with the complex challenges of meeting human food needs in a resource-efficient manner that is economically sound, environmentally benign and socially acceptable.  \nThe double degree Agroecology is a European master's especially for students with a strong interest in sustainable agriculture and agroecosystem management. This programme is connected to the master Resilient Farming and Food Systems and gives the possibility to understand structure and function of complex agroecosystems. When you choose the double degree programme Agroecology you will complete your first year in Wageningen. The second year is taught at ISARA in Lyon, France. The MSc Thesis is co-supervised by WUR and ISARA. This enables to take full advantage of the strengths of Wageningen University & Research and ISARA-Lyon.

OMSCHRIJVING: De master Docent Hoger Gezondheidszorg Onderwijs (HGZO) leidt op tot een innoverende docent die een brug kan slaan tussen onderwijs, (praktijkgericht) onderzoek en de zorg- of welzijnpraktijk.\n\nDe tweejarige deeltijdopleiding master Docent Hoger Gezondheidszorg Onderwijs leidt op tot een innoverende docent met de graad Master of Education. In het programma van de master Docent Hoger Gezondheidszorg Onderwijs staan de competenties didactisch handelen, innoveren, (praktijkgericht) onderzoeken en professionaliseren centraal.

ONDERWIJSBESTUUR_NAAM: Het College van Bestuur van de Vrije Universiteit
OMSCHRIJVING: Leer met welke theoretische inzichten je een scherpe bedrijfskundige visie formuleert in een continue veranderend bedrijfsleven\n\nTijdens deze master leer je waarom organisaties die in dezelfde markt opereren, verschillen in hun succes. Waar komt dit verschil vandaan? Is dit verschil te verklaren uit de wijze waarop de afstemming van mens, geld en technologie in een bepaalde omgeving plaatsvindt: het organiseren? Wat is eigenlijk succesvol opereren? De omgeving van de organisatie is niet stabiel. Er komen concurrenten bij of vallen weg. Maatschappelijke ontwikkelingen zoals duurzaamheid beïnvloeden de vrijheidsgraden in het handelen van een organisatie. Deze complexiteit is het werkveld van de bedrijfskundige. De vraagstukken zijn per definitie multidisciplinair en zelden vanuit één discipline te benaderen. Het curriculum is gebaseerd op drie wetenschappelijke disciplines: - Organisatiekunde - Technologie - Economie Je leert bedrijfskundige vraagstukken multidisciplinair te benaderen. Vervolgens specialiseer je je in een thema: management studies, digital business and innovation, marketing management of financial management. De opleiding is geschikt voor jou als je behoefte hebt aan academische kennis en kunde op het gebied van strategie & organisatie, gedragswetenschappen, technologie en economie.

NAAM_LANG: Executive Master of Finance and Control
INTERNATIONALE_NAAM: Executive Master of Finance and Control
EIGENNAAM: Executive Master in Finance and Control - Jaar 1
OMSCHRIJVING:
Het motto van de Controllersopleiding aan de VU is al sinds jaar en dag: Als je weet wat je te wachten staat en daar adequaat mee om kunt gaan ben je als executive in finance op de toekomst voorbereid

De volgende vier thema’s staan centraal:
1. Digitalisering en robotisering
2. Toenemende hoeveelheden en pluriformiteit van data
3. Fact based en evidence based plan- en besluitvorming
4. Finance als betrouwbare operationele en strategische gesprekspartner van het managen
Tijdsinvestering
Een reguliere vrijdag kent 6 uur college. Ieder uur college vraagt 1½ tot 2 uur aan voorbereiding. Voorbereiding vraagt dus zo'n 9 tot 12 uur en is vooral bedoeld om met elkaar de materie te bespreken en te reflecteren op de impact daarvan op het werk. Je werkt in teams van 3 of 4 studenten.
Docententeam
§ Het docententeam bestaat uit academici die veel ervaring hebben met concernorganisaties en daarnaast nauwgezet de ontwikkelingen van het vak volgen. De studie-inhoud wordt op actuele ontwikkelingen afgestemd.
§ De docenten hebben een gemeenschappelijke kijk op organisaties, de rol van de controller daarin en de didactische aanpak die nodig is om de controller te wapenen tegen veranderende omstandigheden.
§ Ze halen de studenten uit hun comfortzone en leren hen omgaan met gevoelens van onbehagen en onzekerheid.

ONDERWIJSBESTUUR_NAAM: Het College van Bestuur van de Vrije Universiteit
OMSCHRIJVING: De cursus ‘Epidemiologisch onderzoek: basisprincipes’ stelt de belangrijkste principes van epidemiologisch onderzoek aan de orde.\n\nDe cursus ‘Epidemiologisch onderzoek: basisprincipes’ stelt de belangrijkste principes van epidemiologisch onderzoek aan de orde. De deelnemers verwerven inzicht in de belangrijkste begrippen, methoden en technieken van epidemiologisch onderzoek. De onderwerpen die tijdens de cursus behandeld worden, vormen samen de kern van zowel de algemene als de klinische epidemiologie. De rol van de epidemiologie bij de evaluatie van diagnostische tests komt in deze cursus tevens aan de orde. Daarnaast zullen ook de onderzoeksmethodieken naar de effectiviteit van behandelingen besproken worden. De voorbeelden die tijdens de colleges en in het kader van de opdrachten gebruikt worden om de theorie te illustreren, hebben zowel betrekking op gezondheidsproblemen zoals die zich manifesteren in de kliniek, als op thema’s afkomstig uit de ‘public health’-sfeer.

ONDERWIJSBESTUUR_NAAM: Het College van Bestuur van de Vrije Universiteit
Het College van Bestuur van de Vrije Universiteit
OMSCHRIJVING: De Masteropleiding Epidemiologie richt zich op professionals en onderzoekers die werken in de gezondheidszorg in de ruimste zin van het woord; preventie, curatie, revalidatie, beleid en management\n\nHet doel van de Masteropleiding Epidemiologie is het opleiden van kwalitatief goede onderzoekers die in staat zijn om onderzoeksvragen uit de praktijk van de gezondheidszorg en volksgezondheid om te zetten naar een adequate onderzoeksopzet, dit onderzoek uit te voeren, en/of de uitvoering hiervan te coördineren. Zij kunnen hierdoor een relevante bijdrage leveren aan het oplossen van vraagstukken op het gebied van ziekte en gezondheid.

ONDERWIJSBESTUUR_NAAM: Het College van Bestuur van de Vrije Universiteit
OMSCHRIJVING: In deze 6-daagse cursus worden de basisprincipes van multilevel analyse besproken en een aantal specifieke toepassingen daarvan.\n\nIn deze 6-daagse cursus worden de basisprincipes van multilevel analyse besproken en een aantal specifieke toepassingen daarvan. Daarnaast zal veel aandacht worden besteed aan het analyseren van longitudinale data, waarbij zowel standaard als alternatieve modellen worden besproken. Tot slot zal ook veel aandacht worden gegeven aan het analyseren van RCT data.

OMSCHRIJVING: IT Audit Compliance & Advisory (ITACA) is een brede academische MSc-opleiding die je een goed beeld geeft van de complexe samenhang tussen bedrijfseconomie, IT en accountancy.\n\nJe leert, onderzoekt en communiceert over de theorie én de praktijk van IT-audit, compliance & -advisory. Dit doe je in samenwerking met je medestudenten en topdocenten uit de praktijk.
